With the esception of a handful of counties, majority have a roughly even split between percent male and percent female residents.

On the other hand, there is a large variance in race and ethnicity makeups by county. With White and Hispanic/Latino groups being the dominant group in a county most often, a handful of counties have a notable dominance by the Native American or Asian group. Black group is a population minority in all counties.

How does the housing situation vary by county?

Note: The housing data is not available for all counties, and the counties without data were omitted.

Majority of the housing units are relatively new across most of the counties. San Francisco and LA counties, however, have relatively more of older housing units than other counties.

The number of occupants per room within a house is dominantly 1 or less across all counties. A few counties, e.g., Monterey, have a higher percentage of housing units where the occupants per room is greater than 1, signaling a more populated housing environment.

Note: Occupants per room columns are formatted as characters.

COVID-19

Surprisingly, some of the top counties by COVID confirmed cases and deaths per 100K are not the most-populated counties. Furthermore, ranking of confimed cases and deaths did not always align, e.g, LA county had the 9th highest number of confirmed cases per 100K but 3rd highest number of deaths from COVID, signaling either disparity in access to testing or a challenge with treating confirmed patients.
